  <static seed="48" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/Factoring/factoring30.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the greatest common factor of the following terms.</p>
<p><m>{9x^{13}y^{8}}</m>, <m>{-36x^{11}y^{10}}</m>, <m>{90x^{6}y^{13}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>9x^{6}y^{8}\hbox{ or }-9x^{6}y^{8}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>There are three things to look for in this problem:
<ul label="disc">
<li>
<p>the greatest common <em>numerical</em> factor is <m>9</m></p>
</li>
<li>
<p>the greatest common power of <m>x</m> is <m>x^{6}</m>, since it has the <em>lowest</em> exponent.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>the greatest common power of <m>y</m> is <m>y^{8}</m>, since it has the <em>lowest</em> exponent.</p>
</li>
</ul></p>
<p>The greatest common factor of the three terms is <m>{9x^{6}y^{8}\hbox{ or }-9x^{6}y^{8}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
